{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205696398/1930103101/0379.xml":{"full_text":"COOLIDGE SURE\nNO ONE GOULD\nAVOID SLUMP\nSPRINGFIELD, Mass., Oct. 31.\nNothing that Federal or State\ngovernments could have done\nwould have prevented the present\nbusiness depression, former Presi\ndent Calvin Coolidge said in a\nradio address last night.\nSpea* t primarily on the\nqualifications of William M. But\nler, Republican senatorial candi\ndate, Coolidge attributed the\ntrade recession to \u201cthat secondary\nreaction which has usually fol\nlowed the first revival after great\nwars.\u201d\nHe said:\nBlames World Slump\n\u201cThe present conditions of\nIndustry are not satisfactory.\nWe have been undergoing a re\nadjustment which may be ben\neficial when it is completed,\nbut it is difficult while it is\nin progress.\n\"We have had a world wide\nrecession in trade. It has been\ndue to a combination of causes\nwhich no one yet comprehends.\nThere has been a chronic revo\nlution in China, economic\nchaos in Russia and grave dis\nturbances in India, so that one\nhalf of the population of the\nglobe has been turned into a\nfinancial liability.\nPolicies of Security\n\u201cSouth American states have\nbeen in revolt. These had their\nInfluence, but probably we are\ngoing through that secondary\nreaction which has usually fol\nlowed the first revival after\ngreat wars.\n\u201cNo government worthy of\nconfidence undertakes to guar\nantee prosperity. It can, how\never, through wise measures\npromote security and peace, ac\ncompanied by reasonable taxa\ntion, greatly promote all kinds\nof business. Such a policy will\nmake business better when\ntimes are good and prevent it\nfrom being worse when times\nare bad.\nNo Preventive Found\n\u201cIf there was any action that\ncould have been taken by the\nGovernment of the United\nStates which would have pre\nvented the trouble that has\narisen all over the world, no one\nhas yet convincingly stated it.\n\u201cOs course during a political\ncampaign many claims are made\nbut I do not know of anything\nwhich the Federal or State gov\nernments have failed to do\nwhich either would have pre\nvented the depression or now\nwould cause a healthy revival\nin business.\n\u201cIt is not time for rash ex\nperiments in men or measures.\nWe need public officers of great\nability and even of greater\ncourage who can be trusted to\nsupport measures that expe\nrience has demonstrated are\nwise and sound.\u201d\nCome to the\nARTHUR JORDAN\nPIANO CO.\n1239 G St., at 13th\nAnd record your 'voice on the'\nNEW 71 CTOR RADIO\nCOMBINATION\nVictor\nRadio\nELECTROLA\nHOME RECORDING\nMake Your Own Records at Home\nSee It Now at\nKITT\u2019S\n1330 G St.\nDaily Crossword Puzzle\ni [1 \u2014p \u20145 5 5\ni 4 ib\nt/TZT 1 77\n\nie 40\n55 47\nAcro\u00ab\u00bb\n1 Author of\n\u2022'Teas of the\nd'Urbervillee.\u201d\n6. The Ayrshire\nBard.\n11. Inclose\n13. Medicinal and\nchemical resin.\n14. Wheat grow\ning State (ab.)\n15. Pertaining to\nearth.\n17. Italian river.\nIX. Golf mound.\n30. Author of\n\u2022\u2018Cloieter and\nthe Hearth.\u201d\n21. Appropriate.\n22. River and bat\ntlefield in Rus\nso-Japanese\nWar.\n24. An election out\nof regular\norder.\n25. Allowance for\nwaste.\n26. Centaur whoso\nshirt poisoned\nHercules.\n21. Present King\nof Egypt.\n29. Large contain\ners for liquids\nin. Elia.\n31. Author of\n\u201cMarse Chan.'\n32. French man's\nname.\n34. Short missive.\n35. Funeral vase.\n36. College cheers.\n38. Metric land\nmeasure.\n,39. Author f \"Th\u00bb\nMill on the\nFloss.''\n41. Brief slumber.\n42. Weight (ab.).\n13. Jibed.\n45. Chinese meas\nure of length.\n46. Hero of Ver\ngil\u2019s epic.\n48. Excuse for ab\nsence from\ncourt.\n50. Author of\n*'Rab and His\nFriends.\u201d\n7 Groups to Meet\nAt Unknown's Tomb\nA memorial service at the\nTomb of the Unknown Soldier\nwill be held at 12:15 o clock\nArmistice Day by seven World\nWar welfare agencies, with Dr.\nEdward N. Calisch, of Richmond,\nVa., as principal speaker.\nGeorge G. Cohen, of the Jew\nish Welfare Board, is in charge of\narrangements for the ceremonies.\nOther organizations participating\ninclude the American Library As\nsociation, the National Catholic\nWar Council and Knights of Co\nlubus, the Salvation Army, the\nWar Camp Community, the Young\nMen\u2019s Christian Association, and\nthe Young Women\u2019s Christian As\nsociation.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\n61. Roman gar\nments.\nDowa\n1. English author\nof many he oka\nfor boys.\n2. Pertaining to\na South Amer\nican mountain\nrange.\n3. Red Cross\n(ab.).\n4. Dative (ab.).\n5. Belgian river\nand World War\nbattle-ground.\nYESTERDAY\u2019S ANSWERS\nROBBER TAKES 3 PINTS\nRobbers yesterday battered the\nlock from the cellar door of a\ndrug store in the 300 block East\nCapitol St. S. E., and stole three\npints of whisky.\n6. Polson.\n7. Utilize.\n8 Right (ab.,.\n9. Pinched.\n10. 'The Wizard\nof the North.\u201d\n12. Place of dark\nness (Roman\nmyth).\n13. Native of an\ncient empire\nadjetning Per\nsia.\n16. Radioactive\nbeams.\n19. Raise.\n21. Native of\nArabia.\n23. Custom.\n25. Morbid growth.\n27. Female saint\n(Pl).\n28. Aerating de\nvice.\n30. Glrl\u2019a name.\n31. Bearer.\n32. Kind i1 cheese.\n:3. Muse of com\nedy.\n14. Hindu Prince.\n.'5 Mexican rub\nber trees.\n,7. Twirls.\n39. Ardor.\n10. Determine by\ntrial.\n43. Not many.\n44. British mili\ntary order for\ngallantry (ab\n45. Word of nega\ntion.\n49 Giant King of\nBashan.\nProlix, NEW YORK /WENUE \u00bbt FIFTEENTH\nFl a .x\u00ab aa-ka.k a alb k w l b |l W l| b\"h \u25a0i 9 s'dd'lsa. rr'ry '\"Yi \"\"i'TWII\u2019WSaBMMSEi ft \u25a0\u25a0f kt ,i, aaaWis, j\nKieping'Washington Jlen Dressed\ni\nStylepark a superb hat at any\nj price a compelling hat at $5.\nA ONE PRICE\nA, Thrfefrfyu&jpffia\nN7 Plew York Avenue at Fifteenth\noy Branch Store: 3113 Fourteenth Street N.JF,\nQ NATIONALLY KNOWN\nDAUGHTER GETS\nADAMS RIGHES\nMrs. Estelle P. Adams, who died\nOctober 13, by her will, filed for\nprobate, charged her daughter\nwith the support of her husband,\nByron S. Adams, should his\nhealth fail or should he meet\nwith reverses. Mrs. Adams ex\nplained in her will that Mr.\nAdams had insisted that he be ex\ncluded from its benefits, but she\ngive him a life Interest in her\nfurniture, silver and household\neffects.\nThe daughter, Mrs. Marie A.\nKing, is to have these articles at\nMr. Adams\u2019 death.\nThe sum of SI,OOO is given to\nMonsignor P. C. Gavan, rector of\nthe Shrine of the Sacred Heart\nfor his personal use; SSOO is given\nfor masses and SI,OOO is to be\ndivided equally between upkeep of\nthe chapel of the shrine and\nmasses for the Holtzman family.\nThe Christ Child Society, Catho\nlic Home for Aged Ladles, and\nSt. Vincent\u2019s Orphan Asylum are\ngiven SI,OOO each, and a number\nof bequests are made to relatives.\nThe residue is to be held in\ntrust by Mr. Adams and the Fed\neral-American National Barfk for\nthe benefit of the daughter until\nshe reaches the age of 50 years,\nwhen she Is to be given one-half\nof the estate outright and the in\ncome from the remainder until\nher death when it is to be held\nfor the benefit of her children.\nTitles for Federal\nLots Are Approved\nAnnouncement was made yes\nterday that the Department of\nJustice has approved titles to two\nparcels of land acquired by the\nFederal Government here.\nOne lot in the square sur\nrounded by Louisiana Avenue, B\nStreet, and Ninth and Tenth\nStreets Northwest was obtained\nfrom Mr. and Mrs. Harry Berman\nfor inclusion in the triangle\nbuilding program. The other, just\nbehind the Library of Congress,\nbought from C. F. Braulik, is to\nbe used for the Botanical Garden.\nThe respective purchase prices\nwere $43,408 and $5,205.\nSHipTINESMERGE\nSAN FRANCISCO, Oct. 31 (I.\nN.S.).\u2014Consolidation of the Mat\nson Navigation Company and the\nLos Angeles Steamship Company\nhad been completed today, making\nthe Matson company the largest\nsteamship organization operating\nin the American Merchant Marine.\nThe National Mv\nLou Gehrig Resting\nAfter 2 Operations\nNEW YORK, Oct. SI (IHJS.).\nLou Gehrig, star first baseman of\nthe New York Yankees, was re\nported resting easily today fol\nlowing two minor operations.\nA fragment of bone was re\nmoved from Gehrig\u2019s right elbow\nand a fracture dislocation of the\nright small finger was reduced.\n9rony NEW YGBK yWENUEof HFTEENBi\n\u00aeW/'itaserf\nTRufJXv\niO B Teck-Six popularity is\nW 3 a no accident. These\n1 fine shoes have earned\nJK 4 dPttOw\u00dfl their position by con-\nBd ]3Bi\u00dfil sistent adherence to\nK Rood style, good leath-\nSL ers and skilled crafts-\nV OwO M manship.\nThey are shoes for\nmen who want com-\nV* S fort with their style.\nW J\n'3L S Black or tan; leather\nor heels; eight\nstyles; all $6.\nNew York Avenue at Fifteenth\nNAT TONALLY KN OWN'\nFRIDAY\u2014OCTOBER 31\u20141930\nLast Rites Held\nFor L. R, Wolford\nROCKVILLE. Md., Oct. 81.\nFuneral services were held today\nat the W. R. Pumphrey, jr., Colon\nial funeral home for Lewis R. Wol\nford, 19, of the 4600 block Ridge\nStreet, Chevy Chase, Md., who died\nWednesday morning, after an ill\nness of more than a year. Inter\nment was in Rockville Union Ceme\ntery.\n9ro/iy NEW YORK\nKeeping yfahington Aten 'WeH'Dressed\nI* Jr\ngig\nfJI\nW\n\\w B\n1B B B\nI\nThere\u2019s a Big\nStory Back of\n'35\nSuper-Value Suits did not \u201cjust\nhappen.\u201d In the production of\nthese suits we chose our best\ncraftsmen, put into their hands\nour personal selection of wool\nens, drawn from grades that\nnormally belong to much higher\nranges, and specified that more\nthan twenty hand operations\nshould be included in their\nmaking.\nThe result is a distinct achieve\nment both in intrinsic value and\nfashion expression. We believe\nSuper-Value Two-Trouser Suits\nINCOMPARABLE AT THE\nPRICE.\nFinished and unfinished wors\nteds, cheviots, cassimeres and\nserges in new patterns or plain\ncolors.\nIn all sizes\u2014up to 48 \u2014in 